export const SEARCH_INDEX = [{"u":"vintage-story.html","p":"The Drifter's Almanac","s":"The Drifter's Almanac","k":"A complete, interactive fan-made field guide to Vintage Story 1.22.3 (standard world, Commoner class): stone-age survival, the full Stone→Copper→Bronze→Iron→Steel progression, knapping & clay forming & smithing, mechanical power, food & farming, base & cellar build plans, temporal stability, biomes, the bestiary, ruins and traders."},{"u":"vs-architect.html","p":"The Architect","s":"The Architect","k":"A complete decorative-building guide for Vintage Story 1.22.3: chiseling, material palettes early to late game, roofs, timber-frame walls, windows & lighting, interiors & furniture, six build styles with material recipes, and a full step-by-step cottage build — all with interactive top-down plans and palette boards."},{"u":"vs-architect.html#overview","p":"The Architect","s":"What Makes a Build Beautiful","k":"Pretty builds in Vintage Story aren't about rare blocks — they're about four levers you can pull with materials you already have. Internalise these and even a cob hut looks intentional."},{"u":"vs-architect.html#chisel","p":"The Architect","s":"The Chisel","k":"The chisel is the single most important tool for good-looking builds. Crafted from metal, it lets you carve any solid block into microblocks — each full block is a 16×16×16 grid of voxels you can remo"},{"u":"vs-architect.html#palettes","p":"The Architect","s":"Palettes, Early → Late","k":"Your palette grows with your tech. Here's what's available when, and how each tier looks — pick a small set and repeat it."},{"u":"vs-architect.html#roofs","p":"The Architect","s":"Roofs","k":"Nothing rescues or ruins a build faster than the roof. A flat slab roof says \"unfinished\"; a pitched, overhanging, textured roof says \"home.\" The plan below is a hip roof — it steps inward as it rises"},{"u":"vs-architect.html#walls","p":"The Architect","s":"Walls With Depth","k":"The biggest single upgrade to any build is breaking up flat walls. The classic technique is timber framing ( fachwerk ): a grid of dark beams with plaster infill, on a stone base course . Below is a f"},{"u":"vs-architect.html#openings","p":"The Architect","s":"Windows, Doors & Light","k":"Plain glass early; leaded/coloured glass later. Frame each window with a chiseled timber or stone surround and add shutters — even fake ones add depth."},{"u":"vs-architect.html#interiors","p":"The Architect","s":"Interiors & Furniture","k":"An empty box never looks finished. Vintage Story's storage is decoration — barrels, crocks, shelves and cabinets (voxel-placed in 1.22) all double as set dressing. Here's a cozy single-room layout, to"},{"u":"vs-architect.html#styles","p":"The Architect","s":"Six Styles + Material Recipes","k":"A style is just a fixed palette + a roof shape. Steal one of these wholesale, early to late."},{"u":"vs-architect.html#cottage","p":"The Architect","s":"Full Build: The Timber-Frame Cottage","k":"A complete, copyable build that uses everything above: a stone base course, white-plaster-and-beam walls, glass windows, a log-cornered frame and an overhanging shingle roof. Step through the layers, "},{"u":"vs-architect.html#finishing","p":"The Architect","s":"Finishing & Landscaping","k":"The details around a build matter as much as the build. Once the shell is up:"},{"u":"vs-architect.html#rules","p":"The Architect","s":"The Ten Rules (Tick as You Master Them)","k":"Ten habits that turn a survival box into a build. Tick them off as they become second nature — saved in this browser."},{"u":"vs-cheatsheet.html","p":"The Cheat Sheet","s":"The Cheat Sheet","k":"A printable one-page Vintage Story 1.22.3 cheat sheet: the Stone→Steel progression and its gates, alloy ratios, melting & fuel temperatures, tool/anvil tiers, prospecting ladders, temporal-storm numbers, nutrition, cellar & preservation, crop nutrients, the day-one checklist and default controls — all on a single poster you can print or save as PDF."},{"u":"vs-cheatsheet.html#flow","p":"The Cheat Sheet","s":"Stone → Steel, at a glance","k":"Stone Copper Bronze Iron Steel knap · fire pottery · crucible smelt & cast copper pick + anvil alloy in crucible bronze pick + anvil charcoal · bloomery hammer the bloom cementation furnace ~6.67 days"},{"u":"vs-cheatsheet.html#cards","p":"The Cheat Sheet","s":"The Cheat Sheet","k":"Full walkthrough: The First Day"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"Warmth & Wear","k":"A complete Vintage Story 1.22.3 guide to staying warm and staying protected: body temperature and cold damage, clothing warmth values, surviving winter, the eight armor types across the three armor slots, protection tiers, and the leather/linen/wool materials behind it all."},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#overview","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"Two Systems, Same Body","k":"Your equipment screen feeds two completely different survival systems, and confusing them gets people killed in their first winter."},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#cold","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"Body Temperature & Cold","k":"With true winters enabled (the default on Standard), your body temperature must stay at about 37°C . Let it fall and you take steadily mounting cold damage — prolonged exposure can freeze you to death"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#warmth","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"Clothing for Warmth","k":"Each worn clothing piece offsets the effective temperature by its warmth value (shown in green on the tooltip), and the pieces add up . Condition matters: a worn-down garment gives less than a fresh o"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#winter","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"Surviving Winter","k":"Winter is Vintage Story's first true test of preparation. Crops stop and die, water freezes, foraging dries up, and the cold itself becomes lethal. You survive it by having gotten ready in autumn — no"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#armor","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"The Armor System","k":"Armor is separate from warmth clothing and goes in three dedicated slots: Head , Body and Legs . There are eight armor types — four non-metal and four metal — and within the metal types the metal tier"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#materials","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"Leather, Linen & Wool","k":"Both systems are built from the same handful of soft materials. Set up a steady supply and you can keep yourself warm and armored indefinitely."},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#upkeep","p":"Warmth & Wear","s":"Wear & Upkeep","k":"Clothing, armor and tools all degrade with use, and a degraded item underperforms — less warmth, less protection, less durability before it fails."},{"u":"vs-crafting.html","p":"The Four Crafts","s":"The Four Crafts","k":"A hands-on guide to Vintage Story 1.22.3's four hand-craft minigames: knapping stone tool heads, building pottery and crucibles voxel-by-voxel with clay forming, hammering hot iron and steel on the anvil (smithing), and casting copper and bronze tools from a crucible into clay molds. Includes interactive blueprint viewers for each craft."},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#overview","p":"The Four Crafts","s":"Overview","k":"Where Minecraft hands you items from a recipe grid, Vintage Story makes you form them. Each of the four crafts is a small voxel puzzle, and which one you reach for depends entirely on the material and"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#knapping","p":"The Four Crafts","s":"Knapping","k":"Knapping is the first craft anyone does. You lay a loose stone flat as a grid of voxels and chip away everything that isn't the tool , leaving the head behind. No fire, no workbench — just a stone, a "},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#clay","p":"The Four Crafts","s":"Clay Forming","k":"Clay forming is the opposite of knapping: instead of chipping away, you add voxels, building a vessel up layer by layer until it matches the blueprint. It's how you make every piece of pottery — inclu"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#smithing","p":"The Four Crafts","s":"Smithing","k":"Smelting metal isn't enough to make a tool — for iron and steel , you have to shape it solid . You heat an ingot in a forge until it glows, lay it on an anvil , and hammer it to a voxel blueprint, one"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#casting","p":"The Four Crafts","s":"Casting","k":"Casting is the quickest path to metal tools, and the only way to shape copper and bronze : you melt the metal fully liquid in a crucible and pour it into clay molds, then let it cool into a solid part"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html","p":"The Bestiary","s":"The Bestiary","k":"A field bestiary for Vintage Story 1.22.3: how combat and damage tiers work, the prey you hunt for meat, hide and resources, the predators that hunt you (wolves, hyenas, bears), temporal and hostile creatures (drifters, locusts, rift creatures), the new freshwater fish, and animal husbandry — taming, breeding and butchering to start a farmstead."},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#combat","p":"The Bestiary","s":"Combat & Damage Tiers","k":"Fighting in Vintage Story isn't about raw hit-point swings — it's a game of tiers . Almost every attack lands at a damage tier (roughly 1, 2 or 3 ), and your armour reduces incoming damage by tier . M"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#prey","p":"The Bestiary","s":"Prey & Passive Animals","k":"These animals won't hurt you — they're walking food, hide and resources. The challenge is catching them: most are skittish and bolt the moment you're spotted. Approach low, open with a thrown spear or"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#predators","p":"The Bestiary","s":"Predators","k":"Three wild predators will actively come for you. Early on — before armour and metal weapons — they are the most likely thing to kill you in daylight. Know which is which, and never let a fight happen "},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#temporal","p":"The Bestiary","s":"Temporal & Hostile Creatures","k":"Not everything here is an animal. The world's broken time bleeds drifters , cave locusts and rift creatures into reality. These are the monsters of Vintage Story — and dealing with them is bound up wi"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#fish","p":"The Bestiary","s":"Fish","k":"Version 1.22 added fishing , and with it a whole new tier of prey: 20+ freshwater fish species living in rivers and lakes, with location-specific populations and their own bait preferences ."},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#husbandry","p":"The Bestiary","s":"Animal Husbandry","k":"Once you can survive the wildlife, you can raise it. Husbandry turns the hunt into a renewable supply: tame animals by feeding them at a trough , breed them across generations , and butcher the surplu"},{"u":"vs-food.html","p":"The Larder","s":"The Larder","k":"A complete guide to eating well in Vintage Story 1.22.3: the saturation bar and the five nutrition groups that raise your max health, foraging and hunting for early food, farming and soil fertility (nitrogen/phosphorus/potassium) with crop rotation and fertilizers, cooking on the fire pit / cooking pot / clay oven, the new 1.22 fishing overhaul, and a pointer to food preservation."},{"u":"vs-food.html#overview","p":"The Larder","s":"Saturation & Nutrition","k":"Hunger in Vintage Story is two systems stacked on top of each other. You manage saturation — the bar that drains as you move, mine and fight — and five separate nutrition bars . Keeping them all toppe"},{"u":"vs-food.html#groups","p":"The Larder","s":"The Five Nutrition Groups","k":"Every edible item belongs to one or more of five groups: Fruit, Vegetable, Protein, Grain and Dairy . Each group fills its own bar as you eat foods of that type. The combined fullness of those bars se"},{"u":"vs-food.html#foraging","p":"The Larder","s":"Foraging & Hunting","k":"Your first meals come from the land as it is. Foraging covers four nutrition groups before you've turned a single clod of soil, and a little hunting handles protein."},{"u":"vs-food.html#farming","p":"The Larder","s":"Farming & Soil Fertility","k":"To farm, take a hoe to grass-covered soil to till it into farmland , plant a seed, and let water (or rain) plus warmth grow it. The catch — and the heart of farming — is that soil isn't infinite. Each"},{"u":"vs-food.html#cooking","p":"The Larder","s":"Cooking","k":"Raw ingredients are survival; cooked meals are where food becomes efficient — more satiety per item, better nutrition, and far longer shelf life. There are three cookers, each for a different job."},{"u":"vs-food.html#fishing","p":"The Larder","s":"Fishing","k":"Version 1.22 brought a full fishing overhaul : 20+ freshwater fish species with location-specific populations and their own bait and lure preferences . Fish are a reliable, renewable source of the pro"},{"u":"vs-food.html#fresh","p":"The Larder","s":"Keeping It Fresh","k":"Every food spoils over time. Preservation doesn't just delay that — it can extend shelf life dramatically, turning a glut of summer harvest into winter survival. The full preservation system and the c"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html","p":"The First Day","s":"The First Day","k":"A step-by-step first-day survival guide for Vintage Story 1.22.3 (Standard world, Commoner class): controls and the Survival Handbook, knapping your first knife and axe, cordage, building and lighting a fire pit, finding safe food, building a first-night shelter (with an interactive build plan), and the temporal-stability basics that keep you alive."},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#what","p":"The First Day","s":"What This Game Is","k":"Vintage Story looks like a voxel survival game and shares the grid, but it plays like a patient simulation of the Stone Age clawing its way toward the Iron Age. If you arrive expecting Minecraft, thre"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#class","p":"The First Day","s":"You, the Commoner","k":"At character creation you pick a class . This guide assumes the Commoner — the default and the best first character. In the game's own words, Commoners \"are generalists from a multitude of backgrounds"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#controls","p":"The First Day","s":"Controls & the Handbook","k":"The controls are close to other voxel games with a few important twists — especially Shift , which does double duty as sneak and the \"place a knapping/crafting surface\" modifier."},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#tools","p":"The First Day","s":"Knap Your First Tools","k":"Everything starts with knapping : shaping a loose stone into a tool head by chipping away voxels, then lashing that head to a stick . Your two priorities are a knife (harvests grass, reeds, berries an"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#fire","p":"The First Day","s":"Fire & Light","k":"Fire cooks your food, lights your shelter and keeps you warm as nights get cold. You need three things: dry grass , firewood , and a firestarter ."},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#food","p":"The First Day","s":"Food on Day One","k":"You won't farm today. Day-One calories come from foraging and a little hunting . Aim for a mix so your nutrition bars don't run dry."},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#shelter","p":"The First Day","s":"A First-Night Shelter","k":"You don't need a house tonight — you need walls, a roof, a door and light . The fastest shelter is a small dirt or cobblestone box dug into a hillside, with the fire pit inside for light and warmth. B"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#night","p":"The First Day","s":"Surviving the Night","k":"The danger after dark is drifters — shambling temporal creatures that spawn in low light — and surface predators like wolves . Your shelter plus a fire handles drifters; wolves you simply don't go out"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#checklist","p":"The First Day","s":"Day-One Checklist","k":"Eight things, in order. Tick them as you go — your progress is saved in this browser, so you can leave and come back. Finish all eight before you sleep and Day One is a clean success."},{"u":"vs-glossary.html","p":"Glossary","s":"Glossary","k":"An A–Z glossary of Vintage Story 1.22.3 terms — anvil, bloomery, cementation, crucible, drifter, knapping, prospecting pick, temporal stability and more — each with a one-line definition and a deep link to the chapter that explains it."},{"u":"vs-locations.html","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"Ruins & Wayfarers","k":"A field guide to what's out there in Vintage Story 1.22.3: surface and underground ruins and their cracked clay vessels (rare seeds, gears, tools), repairing translocators for long-distance travel, wandering trader caravans and what each type stocks, the new 1.22 dynamic dungeon, spoiler-light story locations, and a packing list for a long expedition."},{"u":"vs-locations.html#overview","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"Overview","k":"Vintage Story's wilderness isn't empty scenery. Scattered across it are four kinds of place worth travelling to — and almost everything rare or strange you'll ever own comes from one of them."},{"u":"vs-locations.html#ruins","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"Ruins, Surface & Deep","k":"Ruins are crumbling stone, cobble and brick structures left by people who came before. Some sit out in the open — a few broken walls, a collapsed tower, an overgrown foundation. Others are buried, rea"},{"u":"vs-locations.html#translocators","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"Translocators","k":"Sooner or later you'll find a translocator in a ruin — a tall, broken teleporter frame, dark and inert. Many are static translocators : each one is permanently wired to a partner translocator somewher"},{"u":"vs-locations.html#traders","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"Wandering Traders","k":"Out on the surface you'll come across trader caravans and tents that spawn in the world. Each trader specialises , and you deal with them using gears (rusty and temporal) and coins as currency. They h"},{"u":"vs-locations.html#dungeon","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"The Dynamic Dungeon","k":"Version 1.22 added a brand-new exploration target: a fully dynamic dungeon that now generates in survival worlds. Unlike the older ruins — which are pre-built structures dropped into the terrain — thi"},{"u":"vs-locations.html#story","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"Story Locations","k":"Vintage Story has a quiet, authored story woven through its world, tied to the temporal mystery — why reality frays, where the gears and drifters come from, who built the translocators. You don't get "},{"u":"vs-locations.html#kit","p":"Ruins & Wayfarers","s":"An Explorer's Kit","k":"A ruin two hundred metres away is a quick raid; a translocator hop or a dungeon delve can strand you somewhere unfamiliar with night coming. Before any long expedition, pack like you might not get str"},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html","p":"The Turning World","s":"The Turning World","k":"A practical guide to mechanical power in Vintage Story 1.22.3: how a network of generators, transmission and consumers shares one rotating speed; building windmills (sails on a rotor) and the new waterwheel + small 4-way hub; turning power 90° with angled gears; powering the quern, grindstone, helve hammer and pulverizer; and a concrete power budget (2–3 sail sets to run a helve hammer) with interactive top-down schematics."},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html#overview","p":"The Turning World","s":"How A Network Works","k":"A mechanical network is a single chain of three roles, and every connected block spins at one shared speed . Get the picture of that chain in your head and everything else is just plumbing."},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html#generators","p":"The Turning World","s":"Generators","k":"A generator is whatever first puts torque into the chain. You have three, in roughly ascending order of effort and output."},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html#transmission","p":"The Turning World","s":"Transmission","k":"Transmission is how rotation gets from the generator to the machine. The pieces are simple and they snap together along the grid."},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html#consumers","p":"The Turning World","s":"Consumers","k":"These are the machines worth automating. Each one can be hand-driven in a pinch, but mechanical power is what turns them from chores into a standing workshop."},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html#budget","p":"The Turning World","s":"Power Budget","k":"The single most common beginner mistake is too little wind for too heavy a machine — usually the helve hammer. Here is roughly what it takes to move one, and why 1.22 made the whole thing far less twi"},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html#build","p":"The Turning World","s":"Build It","k":"The classic first power line. Build the generator high, drop the power down, turn it into your workshop. Schematic (A) is this exact run, top-down."},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html#example","p":"The Turning World","s":"Worked Example — Automate The Smithy","k":"The pay-off build. One windmill, one main line, and the two grindiest jobs in the game run themselves — with a side branch you can switch on only when you need it."},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"Fire & Metal","k":"The Vintage Story metalworking guide for v1.22.3: the heat ladder from rock to steel — ores and where they hide, the fire-clay crucible and smelting, bronze alloy ranges (tin, bismuth, black), clay molds and casting, the 1.22 forge overhaul (bellows, tongs, quenching & tempering), anvil tiers, charcoal pits, the bloomery, the new blast furnace, and the cementation furnace that turns iron into blister steel."},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#overview","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"Overview · The Heat Ladder","k":"Metalworking is a ladder, and the rungs are temperatures. Each new metal demands a hotter heat source and a tougher anvil than the one before — and the two great families of metal are worked in comple"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#ores","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"Ores & Where They Hide","k":"Before you can smelt anything you need ore, and ore is mostly underground. A few rules govern the search: surface metal nuggets are a clue that a vein lies below them; ore must be mined with a metal p"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#crucible","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"The Crucible & Smelting","k":"To melt ore you need a crucible : a fire-clay vessel that holds your ore nuggets while heat does the work. You form it from fire clay on the clay-forming grid and harden it in a pit kiln before it can"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#alloying","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"Alloying · Bronze","k":"Pure copper is soft. Mix the right metals in the crucible — within tight in-game percentage ranges — and you get bronze , the workhorse of the early metal age. Fill the crucible with nuggets in the ri"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#molds","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"Molds & Casting","k":"Casting is how copper and bronze become objects. You pour molten metal from the crucible into a clay mold , let it cool, and pop out the result. Molds are reusable — clay-formed and pit-kiln fired lik"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#forge","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"The Forge 1.22 overhaul","k":"The forge is where you bring ingots, blooms and partly-worked metal up to working temperature before taking them to the anvil. It doesn't melt metal for casting — it heats solid metal so it can be ham"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#anvil","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"The Anvil & Smithing Iron","k":"You cannot smith anything without an anvil , and the anvil's tier matters : an anvil works its own metal tier and one tier above it — so a bronze anvil can shape the higher-tier iron, but a copper anv"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#charcoal","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"Charcoal","k":"Charcoal is the fuel that unlocks the high-temperature half of the ladder. It's the bloomery's only fuel and the carbon source for steel — so before you smelt iron, you make charcoal. You make it by s"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#bloomery","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"The Bloomery","k":"Iron can't be cast and can't be melted in a crucible, so it's smelted in a built bloomery : a furnace that reduces iron ore into a spongy iron bloom . The bloom isn't a finished ingot — it has to be h"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#blast","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"The Blast Furnace 1.22","k":"The blast furnace smelts iron ore into iron more efficiently and in larger batches than a bloomery. It uses bellows to drive its heat, and it's the volume-production answer once you've outgrown one-bl"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#steel","p":"Fire & Metal","s":"Steel & the Cementation Furnace","k":"Steel is iron with carbon driven into it, and you make it in a cementation furnace . The process — carburizing — packs iron ingots into the furnace's \"coffin\" surrounded by charcoal , then keeps the w"},{"u":"vs-progression.html","p":"The Long Road","s":"The Long Road","k":"The master Vintage Story progression guide for v1.22.3: the five ages from bare hands to steel. Concrete, numbered steps through the Stone, Copper, Bronze, Iron and Steel ages — pottery and crucibles, smelting and casting, the bronze alloy ratios, bloomeries and charcoal, cementation furnaces and blister steel — with one big saved checklist that tracks every milestone."},{"u":"vs-progression.html#overview","p":"The Long Road","s":"How to Read This Road","k":"Vintage Story gates its whole tech tree behind metal. There is no \"tech you research\" — there is only the next metal, and each one is harder to get hot, harder to shape, and stronger than the last. In"},{"u":"vs-progression.html#stone","p":"The Long Road","s":"The Stone Age","k":"You begin in the Stone Age with nothing but knapped flint. The goal of this age is not metal — it's the pottery that lets you handle metal: a fired crucible to melt ore in, and clay molds to pour it i"},{"u":"vs-progression.html#copper","p":"The Long Road","s":"The Copper Age","k":"Copper is the first metal and the most forgiving: it shows up as native nuggets on the surface , and it melts cool enough that a humble fire pit can do it. This age turns your fired crucible into your"},{"u":"vs-progression.html#bronze","p":"The Long Road","s":"The Bronze Age","k":"Bronze is copper improved with a second (or third) metal. It's stronger and more durable than pure copper — and, decisively, bronze is the only way into iron twice over : you need a bronze pickaxe to "},{"u":"vs-progression.html#iron","p":"The Long Road","s":"The Iron Age","k":"Iron is the first metal you cannot cast — its melting point is too high for a crucible-and-fire-pit setup. Instead you smelt ore into a spongy \"bloom\" in a bloomery , then hammer that bloom on an anvi"},{"u":"vs-progression.html#steel","p":"The Long Road","s":"The Steel Age","k":"Steel is iron with carbon driven into it. You make it by carburizing iron ingots in a cementation furnace — packing them in charcoal and baking them for days — to get blister steel , which (like an ir"},{"u":"vs-progression.html#power","p":"The Long Road","s":"Mechanical Power","k":"Running parallel to the metal ladder is mechanical power — gears, axles and rotational machines that automate the grind. You start it by hand in the Stone Age and scale it up to water and wind by the "},{"u":"vs-progression.html#next","p":"The Long Road","s":"What's Next","k":"Reaching steel isn't the end of the world — it's when the world starts pushing back. Two systems scale with your progress and deserve a read once your forge is humming."},{"u":"vs-questline.html","p":"The Questline","s":"The Questline","k":"A chapter-by-chapter, FTB-Quests-style quest book for Vintage Story 1.22.3: ten chapters of tickable objectives, each with the method (how) and the reward (why), from your first knapped knife to steel, mechanical power, farming, surviving temporal storms and the endgame. Progress saves in your browser."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#how","p":"The Questline","s":"How This Works","k":"This is a companion checklist, not an in-game mod. It works like an FTB-Quests book: chapters unlock roughly in order, and each quest has tasks to finish."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch1","p":"The Questline","s":"Awakening","k":"You start with nothing. Make the first tools, make fire, and live to see Day Two. Full walkthrough: The First Day ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch2","p":"The Questline","s":"Earth & Fire","k":"No metal happens without pottery. Dig clay, shape it, and fire it into the crucible and molds the rest of the tech tree needs. How-to: The Four Crafts → Clay Forming ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch3","p":"The Questline","s":"The Red Metal","k":"Copper is the real start of the game — stone can't mine ore, so a cast copper pickaxe unlocks mining itself. Deep-dive: Fire & Metal and casting ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch4","p":"The Questline","s":"The Alloy Age","k":"Copper alone won't reach iron. You need bronze twice over — a bronze pickaxe to mine iron ore, and a bronze anvil to work it. Recipes: Fire & Metal → Alloying ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch5","p":"The Questline","s":"The Bloom","k":"Iron isn't cast — it's smelted into a spongy bloom and hammered solid. First you need charcoal. Deep-dive: Fire & Metal → Bloomery ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch6","p":"The Questline","s":"The Crucible of Steel","k":"The endgame metal. You carburize iron into blister steel in a cementation furnace, then hammer it into steel. Deep-dive: Fire & Metal → Steel ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch7","p":"The Questline","s":"The Turning World","k":"Stop grinding by hand — build a mechanical network and let wind or water do the work. Deep-dive: The Turning World ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch8","p":"The Questline","s":"Hearth & Harvest","k":"A fed, warm, well-stocked home is what carries you through winter and the late game. Deep-dives: The Larder , The Homestead , Warmth & Wear ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch9","p":"The Questline","s":"Against the Storm","k":"Reality here is unstable. Learn to manage your stability and weather the temporal storms. Deep-dive: The Rust & The Gear ."},{"u":"vs-questline.html#ch10","p":"The Questline","s":"The Wayfarer","k":"The world is full of ruins, traders, teleporters and a buried story. Go find it. Deep-dive: Ruins & Wayfarers ."},{"u":"vs-reference.html","p":"The Codex","s":"The Codex","k":"The definitive Vintage Story 1.22.3 reference: melting points, every alloy ratio, the full ore & host-rock table, fuel temperatures, anvil tiers, prospecting readout ladders, crops & soil nutrients, nutrition & health numbers, meal shelf life, food-preservation multipliers, temporal-storm timings, a creature stat table, all seven character classes, the calendar and default controls — sourced and cross-checked."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#metals","p":"The Codex","s":"Metals & Melting Points","k":"The hard rule of metallurgy: metals that melt at ≤ 1340 °C can be smelted in a crucible and cast into molds; iron, meteoric iron and steel melt above that cap , so they are never cast — they're smithe"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#alloys","p":"The Codex","s":"Alloy Ratios","k":"Alloys are mixed by combining molten metals in a crucible to an exact percentage window — even 0.1% outside the range fails the melt. Tool strength runs black bronze > tin bronze > bismuth bronze > co"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#ores","p":"The Codex","s":"Ores & Host Rocks","k":"Surface metal nuggets hint at a vein below; deeper ores leave no surface clue. Flint/stone tools can't mine ore — you need a copper (or better) pickaxe."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#fuels","p":"The Codex","s":"Fuels & Heat","k":"Two rules first: without a bellows worked, a fuel reaches only ~60% of its rated temperature (so a fire pit needs the bellows to melt copper); and the bloomery accepts any fuel ≥ 1200 °C — charcoal, a"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#anvils","p":"The Codex","s":"Tool Tiers, Anvils & Units","k":"A tool's material sets its tier , and the tier decides three things: how fast it works, how long it lasts, and — for a pickaxe — which ores it can mine at all . Ore has a minimum pick tier: most ores "},{"u":"vs-reference.html#prospect","p":"The Codex","s":"Prospecting-Pick Readouts","k":"Toggle the pick's two modes with the held-item function key (default F ). Density finds the region; node finds the deposit."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#rocks","p":"The Codex","s":"Rock Types","k":"Rock stacks top → bottom as basalt › sedimentary › metamorphic › igneous › kimberlite . Rock family gates which ores can appear and what stone you build with."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#crops","p":"The Codex","s":"Crops & Soil","k":"Vintage Story assigns a drained nutrient per crop — it does not follow the \"leafy=N / root=P / grain=K\" rule of thumb. Rotate N → P → K so each plot's other nutrients recover."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#nutrition","p":"The Codex","s":"Nutrition & Health","k":"You have a saturation bar (energy) and five nutrition bars. A varied diet literally raises your maximum health."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#meals","p":"The Codex","s":"Meals & Preservation","k":"A cooking pot has 4 ingredient slots (up to 6 each / 6 L liquid) and yields up to 6 servings ; the first two slots set the meal type. Preservation factors stack multiplicatively ."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#temporal","p":"The Codex","s":"Temporal Numbers","k":"Full mechanics in The Rust & The Gear ."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#creatures","p":"The Codex","s":"Creature Stats","k":"Damage comes in tiers ; armor applies a flat reduction first, then a percentage, and resists better when its tier meets the attack's. HP values are approximate/community-measured."},{"u":"vs-reference.html#classes","p":"The Codex","s":"The Seven Classes","k":""},{"u":"vs-reference.html#calendar","p":"The Codex","s":"Calendar & World Dimensions","k":""},{"u":"vs-reference.html#controls","p":"The Codex","s":"Default Controls","k":"Every figure here is cross-referenced from the deep-dive chapters of The Drifter's Almanac . Spot something your game disagrees with? Trust the in-game Handbook — numbers are config-tunable and shift "},{"u":"vs-structures.html","p":"The Homestead","s":"The Homestead","k":"A builder's field guide for Vintage Story 1.22.3: building materials (cob, clay & stone brick, planks, chiseling), upgrading the day-one box into a real starter house, storage options, and the all-important food cellar — with the exact cellar scoring mechanics (skylight & cooling), preservation methods, a smithy layout, the pit kiln and charcoal pit, a cold-climate greenhouse and storm-proofing pointers. Five interactive, layer-by-layer build plans."},{"u":"vs-structures.html#basics","p":"The Homestead","s":"Building Basics","k":"Every structure on this page is made from a handful of building blocks. Pick by what you can reach: cheap cob for the first real walls, fired brick and cut stone for permanence, planks for floors and "},{"u":"vs-structures.html#house","p":"The Homestead","s":"The Starter House","k":"Once you have cob or planks, replace the dirt hole with a real house: a footprint big enough for a hearth, a bed and storage, with a door and one window for light. The plan below is a cosy 7×7 — step "},{"u":"vs-structures.html#storage","p":"The Homestead","s":"Storage","k":"You'll outgrow your inventory fast. Vintage Story has distinct containers, and the right one matters for food — some slow spoilage, some don't. Match the container to the job."},{"u":"vs-structures.html#cellar","p":"The Homestead","s":"The Food Cellar","k":"Food rots in real time. A well-built cellar slows that rot dramatically by giving the game an enclosed, dark, cool room to recognise. Build one early — it's the single biggest quality-of-life upgrade "},{"u":"vs-structures.html#preserve","p":"The Homestead","s":"Food Preservation","k":"The cellar slows spoilage; preservation changes the food so it keeps far longer to begin with. Pair the two. The full nutrition and cooking system lives in The Larder — here's the structural side."},{"u":"vs-structures.html#smithy","p":"The Homestead","s":"The Smithy","k":"Metalworking wants a dedicated, fireproof space. Lay it out so heat, anvil and quench form a tight working triangle : pull hot metal from the forge, hammer it on the anvil, quench it in the barrel — a"},{"u":"vs-structures.html#kiln","p":"The Homestead","s":"Kiln & Charcoal Pit","k":"Two ground-built \"structures\" power your early tech: the pit kiln fires your pottery, and the charcoal pit turns logs into the high-heat fuel your forge and bloomery need."},{"u":"vs-structures.html#greenhouse","p":"The Homestead","s":"Greenhouse","k":"Crops stop growing when it's too cold. A greenhouse — a glass-roofed, glass-walled structure over tilled farmland — lets sunlight in while sheltering the soil, extending the growing season into the co"},{"u":"vs-structures.html#storm","p":"The Homestead","s":"Storm-Proofing","k":"During a temporal storm , drifters spawn everywhere — even in daylight, even on the surface. Your homestead is your shelter: a sealed, lit, fully walled base with controllable chokepoints lets you wai"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"The Rust & The Gear","k":"The complete guide to temporal stability in Vintage Story 1.22.3: what drains it (the deep, rifts, temporal storms), how rifts and storms work and how they're telegraphed, drifters and the escalating deep, temporal gears (instant +~30% stability with a knife in your offhand), how to restore stability, storm-proofing your base, and a spoiler-light look at the lore behind the rust world."},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#what","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"What It Is","k":"Temporal stability is a percentage measuring how firmly reality holds together where you are standing. It runs on a 0–150% scale where 100% is neutral — stable surface areas sit at or above 100% (up t"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#drains","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"What Drains Stability","k":"There are exactly three things that pull your stability down. Learn to recognise each one — they have very different rates and very different fixes."},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#rifts","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"Rifts","k":"Temporal rifts are shimmering tears — \"rust world\" phenomena that puncture the boundary between your world and the one that's rusting through it. They appear out in the world (more readily at night an"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#storms","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"Temporal Storms","k":"A temporal storm is a periodic, world-wide event that arrives roughly every ~10–20 in-game days . For its duration, reality frays everywhere and drifters spawn all around you regardless of light level"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#drifters","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"Drifters & the Deep","k":"Drifters are the game's signature hostile — shambling, temporally-corrupted humanoids that spawn in darkness, near rifts, and everywhere during storms. They're manageable one at a time on the surface,"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#gears","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"Temporal Gears","k":"A temporal gear is the most important single item in the temporal system — a dense little clockwork artefact that you obtain two ways: as a drop from drifters (especially during storms) and from trade"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#restore","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"Restoring Stability","k":"Stability isn't a one-way street. It regenerates on its own in safe places, and you have several active ways to top it up. Here's every lever, weakest to strongest."},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#proofing","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"Storm-Proofing Your Base","k":"Because storms are telegraphed, a properly built base turns them from a crisis into a chore. The goal is a sealed, fully-lit, walled refuge with chokepoints you control — somewhere you can stand and p"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#lore","p":"The Rust & The Gear","s":"The Lore","k":"Temporal stability isn't just a survival meter — it's the thread of the whole story. The warping, the gears, the drifters and the deep all point at the same thing: a \"rust world\" bleeding into yours, "},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","k":"Everything new in the Vintage Story 1.22 update (April 2026): the fishing overhaul, the reworked forge with bellows, tongs and quenching & tempering, cementation-furnace steel, waterwheels and spur gears, voxel-placed cabinets, dynamic dungeons, new mushrooms and the fennel & licorice crops — each linked to the chapter that covers it in depth."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#overview","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"The Headline","k":"Four pillars define the update: fishing , a metalworking rework , new mechanisms , and dynamic dungeons — plus a long tail of flora, fauna and quality-of-life."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#fishing","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"Fishing","k":"1.22's flagship feature gives lakes and rivers a purpose. There are 20+ freshwater fish species with location-specific populations and bait/lure preferences."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#forge","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"Forge & Metalworking","k":"Smithing got a ground-up overhaul that adds real depth to the forge."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#power","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"Mechanical Power","k":"Generators, transmission and a power budget are in The Turning World ."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#storage","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"Storage & Decoration","k":"Storage options and where they fit a base are in The Homestead → Storage ; clothing & armor in Warmth & Wear ."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#worldgen","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"Dynamic Dungeons","k":"A fully dynamic dungeon now generates in Survival worlds — a procedurally assembled, multi-room structure with loot and threats, and a varied layout each time rather than a fixed prefab."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#flora","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"Flora & Fauna","k":"Crops are in The Larder ; the animals in The Bestiary ."},{"u":"vs-whatsnew.html#update","p":"What's New in Vintage Story 1.22","s":"Updating Safely","k":"This page summarises the 1.22 line; exact values live in The Codex , and the official patch notes / wiki are ground truth."},{"u":"vs-world.html","p":"The World","s":"The World","k":"How the Vintage Story world is built (v1.22.3): the north–south temperature gradient and rainfall that shape biomes, the main landscapes and what they offer, seasons and surviving your first winter, the vertical world from soil to bedrock, rock types and the ores they host, ore by depth, and a precise how-to for the prospecting pick — density search vs node search, ‰ readings, and a region-then-deposit workflow."},{"u":"vs-world.html#overview","p":"The World","s":"Overview","k":"The world is shaped along two axes, and learning to read both is most of what makes a confident Vintage Story player."},{"u":"vs-world.html#climate","p":"The World","s":"Climate & Temperature","k":"Temperature follows a north–south gradient : it gets hotter as you travel toward the equator and colder as you head toward the poles . Stacked on top of that is altitude — the higher you climb, the co"},{"u":"vs-world.html#landscapes","p":"The World","s":"Landscapes & Biomes","k":"Each landscape that climate produces offers different resources and different dangers. Here are the main ones you'll meet on the surface and what each is good for."},{"u":"vs-world.html#seasons","p":"The World","s":"Seasons & the Calendar","k":"The year is 12 months — three each of spring → summer → autumn → winter . The default month length is 9 days (configurable), making a season 27 days and a full year 108 days . Day length also shifts w"},{"u":"vs-world.html#vertical","p":"The World","s":"The Vertical World","k":"Dig straight down and the world reveals its structure: a thin skin of soil over many courses of rock , sinking through the deep toward bedrock . Sea level sits roughly midway up the column. What you f"},{"u":"vs-world.html#geology","p":"The World","s":"Geology","k":"Rock isn't just background — its type decides which ores can appear in it and what building stone you get. The world's stone comes in three families:"},{"u":"vs-world.html#ore-depth","p":"The World","s":"Ore by Depth","k":"Metals sort themselves roughly by depth. A surface metal nugget is a clue — it means a vein of that metal sits somewhere in the rock below. As a rough rule of thumb:"},{"u":"vs-world.html#propick","p":"The World","s":"Prospecting With the Propick","k":"The prospecting pick (\"propick\") turns digging blind into a directed hunt. Craft one as soon as you can spare the metal — it's the single tool that makes finding ore reliable. It has two modes ; toggl"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#alloys","p":"Glossary · Alloy","s":"Alloy","k":"A mix of molten metals combined in a crucible to an exact ratio. Ratios"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#fuels","p":"Glossary · Anthracite","s":"Anthracite","k":"The hottest natural coal and the longest-burning fuel. Fuels"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#anvil","p":"Glossary · Anvil","s":"Anvil","k":"Where hot metal is smithed. Works its own tier and one above — a bronze anvil shapes iron. Anvil"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#forge","p":"Glossary · Bellows","s":"Bellows","k":"Pumped air that lets a forge reach full heat — without one, fuel hits only ~60%. Forge"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#steel","p":"Glossary · Blister steel","s":"Blister steel","k":"The raw output of the cementation furnace; must be hammered into steel. Steel"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#bloomery","p":"Glossary · Bloom (iron bloom)","s":"Bloom (iron bloom)","k":"The spongy lump a bloomery produces; hammered on an anvil into wrought-iron ingots. Bloomery"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#bloomery","p":"Glossary · Bloomery","s":"Bloomery","k":"The built furnace that smelts iron ore into a bloom. Bloomery"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#ores","p":"Glossary · Bog iron","s":"Bog iron","k":"Surface limonite in wetlands — the easiest first iron. Ores"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#temporal","p":"Glossary · Bowtorn","s":"Bowtorn","k":"A ranged rift creature with a turret attack. Bestiary"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#armor","p":"Glossary · Brigandine","s":"Brigandine","k":"Leather-and-plate metal armor, available from the copper age. Armor"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#alloying","p":"Glossary · Bronze","s":"Bronze","k":"Copper alloyed with tin, or zinc+bismuth, or gold+silver. The gate to iron. Alloying"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#ores","p":"Glossary · Cassiterite","s":"Cassiterite","k":"Tin ore — scarce; the bronze-age bottleneck. Ores"},{"u":"vs-structures.html#cellar","p":"Glossary · Cellar","s":"Cellar","k":"A cool, sealed room that slows food spoilage; scored 100% − skylight − cooling. Cellar"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#steel","p":"Glossary · Cementation furnace","s":"Cementation furnace","k":"Carburizes iron into blister steel over ~6.67 in-game days. Steel"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#charcoal","p":"Glossary · Charcoal pit","s":"Charcoal pit","k":"Firewood buried in soil and smouldered into charcoal; seal within ~30 s. Charcoal"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#clay","p":"Glossary · Clay forming","s":"Clay forming","k":"The voxel minigame that shapes pottery from clay before firing. Clay forming"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#fuels","p":"Glossary · Coke","s":"Coke","k":"Coal baked airtight in a coke oven; the hottest practical fuel. Fuels"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#class","p":"Glossary · Commoner","s":"Commoner","k":"The default class — no bonuses, no penalties. Classes"},{"u":"vs-food.html#cooking","p":"Glossary · Cooking pot","s":"Cooking pot","k":"A fired clay pot for multi-ingredient meals on a fire pit. Cooking"},{"u":"vs-structures.html#preserve","p":"Glossary · Crock","s":"Crock","k":"A pottery container; sealed , it slows spoilage dramatically. Preservation"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#crucible","p":"Glossary · Crucible","s":"Crucible","k":"A fire-clay vessel that melts ore for casting. Crucible"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#combat","p":"Glossary · Damage tier","s":"Damage tier","k":"Attacks rate 1–3; armor reduces by flat amount then percent. Combat"},{"u":"vs-world.html#prospect","p":"Glossary · Density search","s":"Density search","k":"Propick mode reporting an area's ore probability in ‰. Prospecting"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#temporal","p":"Glossary · Drifter","s":"Drifter","k":"The core temporal hostile; six tiers; spawns at light ≤7 and in storms. Bestiary"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#alloys","p":"Glossary · Electrum","s":"Electrum","k":"A decorative gold+silver alloy. Alloys"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#fire","p":"Glossary · Fire pit","s":"Fire pit","k":"Your first cooker and smelter; bellowed, it melts copper. Fire"},{"u":"vs-getting-started.html#fire","p":"Glossary · Firestarter","s":"Firestarter","k":"A bow-drill made from sticks + dry grass to light fires. Fire"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#materials","p":"Glossary · Flax → linen","s":"Flax → linen","k":"Crop processed into twine and linen for clothing. Materials"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#forge","p":"Glossary · Forge","s":"Forge","k":"Heats metal to working temperature for the anvil (1.22: bellows, tongs, temper). Forge"},{"u":"vs-clothing-cold.html#armor","p":"Glossary · Gambeson","s":"Gambeson","k":"Light quilted-cloth armor; a strong, cheap base layer. Armor"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#ores","p":"Glossary · Galena","s":"Galena","k":"Ore yielding lead and silver. Ores"},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html","p":"Glossary · Helve hammer","s":"Helve hammer","k":"Mechanically powered hammer that automates working blooms and blister steel. Mechanical power"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#predators","p":"Glossary · Hyena","s":"Hyena","k":"Tier-2 pack predator of warm regions; ~10-block aggro. Predators"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#anvils","p":"Glossary · Ingot","s":"Ingot","k":"100 units of metal = 20 ore nuggets. Units"},{"u":"vs-progression.html#iron","p":"Glossary · Iron","s":"Iron","k":"Smelted in a bloomery, hammered from a bloom; needs a bronze pick to mine & bronze anvil to work. Iron age"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#rocks","p":"Glossary · Kimberlite","s":"Kimberlite","k":"The deepest rock layer — the only host of diamonds. Rocks"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#knapping","p":"Glossary · Knapping","s":"Knapping","k":"Chipping loose stone into tool heads — the first craft. Knapping"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#ores","p":"Glossary · Limonite","s":"Limonite","k":"Iron ore; the bog/surface form is the easiest early iron. Ores"},{"u":"vs-creatures.html#temporal","p":"Glossary · Locust","s":"Locust","k":"Metal cave insectoid; the Clockmaker class counters it. Bestiary"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#metals","p":"Glossary · Meteoric iron","s":"Meteoric iron","k":"Premium iron-class metal from meteorites; needs an iron pick. Metals"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#casting","p":"Glossary · Molds","s":"Molds","k":"Fired clay forms you pour molten copper/bronze into to cast tools. Casting"},{"u":"vs-world.html#prospect","p":"Glossary · Node search","s":"Node search","k":"Propick mode giving the direction & size of a nearby ore node. Prospecting"},{"u":"vs-food.html#groups","p":"Glossary · Nutrition","s":"Nutrition","k":"Five food groups (fruit/veg/protein/grain/dairy) that raise max health. Nutrition"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#clay","p":"Glossary · Pit kiln","s":"Pit kiln","k":"A burn that fires raw pottery hard enough to use (~10–20 h). Clay forming"},{"u":"vs-world.html#prospect","p":"Glossary · Prospecting pick","s":"Prospecting pick","k":"The tool that reads ore density (region) and nodes (deposit). Prospecting"},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html","p":"Glossary · Pulverizer","s":"Pulverizer","k":"Mechanically powered crusher; boosts ore yield and feeds steel. Mechanical power"},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html","p":"Glossary · Quern","s":"Quern","k":"Hand- or power-driven mill that grinds grain into flour. Mechanical power"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#rifts","p":"Glossary · Rift","s":"Rift","k":"A temporal tear that spawns hostiles and drains stability ~3%/s nearby. Rifts"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#what","p":"Glossary · Rust world","s":"Rust world","k":"The decaying reality bleeding through at zero stability. Temporal"},{"u":"vs-food.html#nutrition","p":"Glossary · Saturation","s":"Saturation","k":"The energy bar (cap 1500) that drains as you act. Nutrition"},{"u":"vs-crafting.html#smithing","p":"Glossary · Smithing","s":"Smithing","k":"Hammering hot metal on an anvil to a Handbook blueprint. Smithing"},{"u":"vs-food.html#farming","p":"Glossary · Soil fertility","s":"Soil fertility","k":"Per-plot N/P/K that crops drain; managed by rotation & fertilizer. Farming"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#steel","p":"Glossary · Steel","s":"Steel","k":"Carburized iron — the top metal tier. Steel"},{"u":"vs-structures.html#storage","p":"Glossary · Storage vessel","s":"Storage vessel","k":"Bulk pottery container; slows spoilage (×0.75 veg, ×0.5 grain). Storage"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#gears","p":"Glossary · Temporal gear","s":"Temporal gear","k":"Drifter/trader drop; restores +30% stability and powers translocators. Gears"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#what","p":"Glossary · Temporal stability","s":"Temporal stability","k":"How firmly reality holds (0–150%; 100% neutral). Temporal"},{"u":"vs-temporal.html#storms","p":"Glossary · Temporal storm","s":"Temporal storm","k":"A telegraphed event spawning drifters everywhere; every ~10–20 days. Storms"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#crops","p":"Glossary · Terra preta","s":"Terra preta","k":"The richest soil (80% fertility); crafted. Crops"},{"u":"vs-locations.html","p":"Glossary · Translocator","s":"Translocator","k":"A repaired teleporter linking two distant points. Locations"},{"u":"vs-reference.html#alloys","p":"Glossary · Tin bronze","s":"Tin bronze","k":"88–92% Cu + 8–12% Sn — the strongest common bronze. Alloys"},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html","p":"Glossary · Waterwheel","s":"Waterwheel","k":"New 1.22 mechanical generator driven by flowing water. Mechanical power"},{"u":"vs-mechanical-power.html","p":"Glossary · Windmill","s":"Windmill","k":"Sail-driven mechanical generator. Mechanical power"},{"u":"vs-metalworking.html#bloomery","p":"Glossary · Wrought iron","s":"Wrought iron","k":"The worked-iron ingot you get by hammering a bloom. Bloomery"}];
